Recognising the importance of the principle of independence for the credibility and quality of public service broadcasting, which is essential for the protection of the rights of the audience and the integrity of the information provided;
Convinced that the independence of public service broadcasting is a necessary condition for the fulfilment of the public service remit, and for the provision of a wide range of information and opinions which are essential to democratic societies,
1. Urges the governments and regulatory authorities of the European Union to ensure that the principle of independence of public service broadcasting is respected in all their policies and decisions, including in relation to the funding and regulation of public service broadcasting;
2. Invites the governments and regulatory authorities of the European Union to promote the development of independent and autonomous means of communication, including through the provision of public service broadcasting, which can reflect a diversity of ideas and opinions;
3. Calls on the governments and regulatory authorities of the European Union to ensure that the independence of public service broadcasting is respected in the development of media policy, including in relation to the provision of funding for public service broadcasting, and to ensure that the principles of independence are fully integrated into the framework of media policy in the European Union;
4. Urges the governments and regulatory authorities of the European Union to promote the development of public service broadcasting at national and regional levels, in order to ensure that the principles of independence are respected and that a wide range of independent and autonomous means of communication are available to all citizens;
5. Invites the governments and regulatory authorities of the European Union to take into account the recommendations of the 4th European Ministerial Conference on Mass Media Policy (Prague, 7-8 December 1994) and to continue to develop the principles on the independence of public service broadcasting in the light of the challenges raised by political, economic and technological change in 21st century Europe.

